\section{Low-Level-Planner node}

The \hlplanner\ node sends \texttt{HighLevelTask} actions to the \linebreak\llplanner\ node, which tries to execute them and sends the result of the execution back to the \hlplanner. The possible results are given at the end of section \ref{hl_execution}. The execution of robot movement is mainly done via the move{\_}base package. The move{\_}base takes goal poses and plans the robot controls to get to this goal poses, considering the map and sensor inputs for obstacle avoidance. If the goal is reached the move{\_}base returns SUCCEEDED and if the goal could not be reached ABORTED is returned. Only during the peek task velocity commands are directly sent to the Turtlebot interface. 

The node runs a loop, which is depicted in figure \ref{ll_planner}. Which messages are processed depends on the currently active task, but the latest \texttt{map} message is always stored to have the most recent map available. After the message precessing code dependent on the task, the received messages and the result of the move{\_}base is executed. This code involves the start of the task execution, the generation and sending of goal poses or velocity commands, and sending of results back to the \hlplanner. At the end of the loop the current action is published to inform the mapping node about the high-level task in execution. In the following sections the implementation of the individual tasks is described in more detail.

\begin{figure}[h]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.25\textwidth,clip]{figures/ll_planner.pdf}
  \caption[Low{\_}level{\_}planner node overview]{Overview over the execution of the \llplanner\ node}
  \label{ll_planner}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Move Through Doorway Task}

The steps of the execution of this task are already described in section \ref{move_trough_doorway_task}. The current state of the execution is stored in a state variable, which can either be STARTED, FIRST{\_}GOAL{\_}REACHED, REACHED{\_}OTHER{\_}ROOM or FINISHED. Depending on the state the goal pose is calculated and sent to the move{\_}base. In figure \ref{drive_through_door_impl} the calculation of the goal poses is depicted. The obstacles in the map are inflated to get the area the robot can drive to. Depending on the state the goal is 0.5\,m in front of the doorway (state = STARTED), 0.5\,m behind the doorway (state = FIRST{\_}GOAL{\_}REACHED) or again 0.5\,m in front of the doorway, but with flipped orientation (state = REACHED{\_}OTHER{\_}ROOM). If the location directly in front of the doorway is inaccessible, goal poses shifted to the side are tested until an accessible pose is found. A state change happens if the goal is reached or the map switch occurs. At every state change a new goal pose is calculated and sent to the move{\_}base. Furthermore, every time a \texttt{dorway{\_}poses} message arrives a new goal pose is calculated. This goal pose is only sent to the move{\_}base if the goal has changed noteworthy. If the move{\_}base fails to execute a movement, the task is aborted. Otherwise, after reaching the final goal, a successful execution is reported to the high-level planner.

\begin{figure}[h]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth,trim=30 50 100 20,clip]{figures/drive_through_door_impl.png}
  \caption[Drive through doorway goal calculation]{Drive through doorway goal calculation: The map and the accessible cells (white) are shown in the background. The doorway poses (green arrow before map switch, purple arrow afterwards) and the goal poses (red arrows) are shown. On the blue lines are the considered goal poses in case the poses directly in front of the doorway are not accessible.}
  \label{drive_through_door_impl}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Peek Task}

In this task velocity commands are sent directly to the Turtlebot interface because collisions are nearly impossible during the in-place rotations executed in this task. At the start of the task the current orientation of the robot is stored. Then a velocity command with zero translational velocity and a low negative rotational velocity is sent repetitively to the robot until a rotation of -90° is done. This is repeated with a positive angular velocity until a rotation of 90° compared to the starting orientation is reached. With an again negative angular velocity the robot is rotated back to the starting position and a successful execution is reported to the high-level planner. During the execution \texttt{high{\_}confidence{\_}objects} messages can be received. If an confident detection of a searched object is received, the task is stopped and object found is reported to the high-level-planner. 

\subsection{Explore Room Task}

Three events can trigger the sending of a new goal pose during the execution of the exploration task. The first is the receipt of a new map. In this case a new goal pose is calculated and if the new pose is significant different than the old goal pose, the goal is sent to the move{\_}base. The second trigger is a failed movement execution. In this case a new goal pose is calculated with exclusion of poses similar to the failed goal pose and sent to the move{\_}base. The third event is triggered if the robot has not moved for a specified time. In this case a problem in the path planning is assumed and this case is handled like the second case.

The calculation of the next goal pose is done according to section \ref{explore_task}. The calculation of the frontiers is shown in figure \ref{frontier_calc}. 
\begin{figure}
\begin{tabular}{ccc}
\subfloat[free cells]{\includegraphics[decodearray={1.0 0.0},width=0.3\textwidth]{figures/expl_impl/free.png}} &
\subfloat[occupied cells]{\includegraphics[decodearray={1.0 0.0},width=0.3\textwidth]{figures/expl_impl/occupied.png}} &
\subfloat[unknown cells]{\includegraphics[decodearray={1.0 0.0},width=0.3\textwidth]{figures/expl_impl/unknown.png}} \\
\subfloat[filtered free cells]{\includegraphics[decodearray={1.0 0.0},width=0.3\textwidth]{figures/expl_impl/free2.png}} &
\subfloat[dilated occupied cells]{\includegraphics[decodearray={1.0 0.0},width=0.3\textwidth]{figures/expl_impl/occupied_dilate.png}}&
\subfloat[dilated unknown cells]{\includegraphics[decodearray={1.0 0.0},width=0.3\textwidth]{figures/expl_impl/unknown_dilate.png}} \\
\subfloat[not-forbidden cells]{\includegraphics[decodearray={1.0 0.0},width=0.3\textwidth]{figures/expl_impl/not_forbidden2.png}} &
\subfloat[accessible cells]{\includegraphics[decodearray={1.0 0.0},width=0.3\textwidth]{figures/expl_impl/accessible.png}}&
\subfloat[frontiers]{\includegraphics[width=0.3\textwidth]{figures/expl_impl/frontiers.png}}
\end{tabular}
\caption{Calculation of the frontiers: In those binary images black is 1 and white is 0; the gray accessible area in the last image is just for orientation}
\label{frontier_calc}
\end{figure}Firstly, the free cells, occupied cells and unknown cells are extracted from the map and converted into OpenCV \texttt{cv::Mat}-images. The image of the free cells is filtered by the morphological operation opening with a circular kernel. The diameter of the kernel is the robot diameter. The image of the occupied cells is dilated using the same kernel. The image of the unknown cells is dilated with a 3x3 kernel, to get an overlap with the free cells. The not-forbidden cells are the filtered free cells minus the dilated occupied cells. Not-forbidden cells are valid locations for the robot. However, these cells need not be accessible because obstacles could block the way to some of those cells. Therefore a flood fill algorithm is executed on the image of the not-forbidden cells with the current robot location being the starting pixel for the flood fill. This results in the cells accessible by the robot, which are identical to the not-forbidden cells in this example. The frontiers are then the intersection of the dilated unknown cells and the accessible cells. 

The goal pose is not set to the nearest frontier. Instead poses near the frontiers are considered, which are depicted in figure \ref{poseses}. This is done to avoid goal poses at the border of accessible space, which have a higher probability to fail. Additionally a penalty is given to cells near the border of accessible space, so those cells are only chosen as goal locations if necessary. The resulting goal pose is the location of the nearest possible goal cell with an orientation towards the frontier. 

\begin{figure}[h]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth,clip]{figures/expl_impl/poseses.png}
  \caption[Possible exploration goals]{Possible location goals are shown in dark gray, accessible cells in light gray and frontiers in black}
  \label{poseses}
\end{figure}

A special case is if the goal pose is within the robots footprint. This can happen as the footprint is not cleared in the mapping. In this case the goal is set to a pose outside the footprint facing towards the frontier.

During the execution \texttt{high{\_}confidence{\_}objects} messages can be received. If an confident detection of a searched object is received, the task is stopped and object found is reported to the high-level-planner. Also \texttt{doorwy{\_}found} messages can be received. In this case the exploration is stopped, so the high-level planner can plan again using the new information.

\subsection{Search Room Task}

In the search task the triggering of the calculation of a new goal pose is slightly different than in the exploration task. Instead of calculating a new goal pose every time a map is received, a new goal pose is calculated and sent if an image taken at the goal pose was processed. 

During the search multiple data structures are maintained. Firstly, an Object-Map is created out of the received \texttt{VisionResult} messages. This is done like in the mapping node, but only for the robot pose, which is assumed to be the true pose, and the searched object type. Also a 3D map is created similar to the creation in the mapping node, but also just for the robot pose. The samples in the \texttt{VisionResult} messages are used as input point clouds for the 3D mapping. Using the \texttt{map} messages, a map of the accessible cells and the border described in section \ref{SearchTask} are created. This border 

In addition to the calculation of the next movement goal an Object-Map and a 3D map are created like in the mapping node, but only for the robot pose, which is assumed to be accurate enough, and the searched object type. Every execution cycle the object probability in all cells is calculated and if the object probability in the cell with the highest probability is greater than a threshold, the object is found and the search is stopped.



Three events can trigger the sending of a new goal pose during the execution of the exploration task. The first is the receipt of a new map. In this case a new goal pose is calculated and if the new pose is significant different than the old goal pose, the goal is sent to the move{\_}base. The second trigger is a failed movement execution. In this case a new goal pose is calculated with exclusion of poses similar to the failed goal pose and sent to the move{\_}base. The third event is triggered if the robot has not moved for a specified time. In this case a problem in the path planning is assumed and this case is handled like the second case.